No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian Parliament today refused the request to abolish the paragraphs on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been convicted in the context of a revision of the Criminal Code.
The new regime, which could have paved the way for the release of the detained ex-prime minister, was rejected by the honourable Members at the second reading of the request to alleviate the penalties for economic crimes.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding a allegedly adverse contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet binding, and in December the appeal of the convicted shall be tried before the court.
Timoshenko himself refers to the judgment as a political revenge of the regime and also in the West the trial raised the suspicion of prejudice of the court.
The request to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was condemned to be in the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 MEPs.
226 votes would have been necessary for its adoption.
