The menu of a obese child: it does not breakfast and eats for dinner sausage
More than a third of children from 9 to 13 have overweight problems, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Current surveys have shown - adipose children usually come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important for the healthy development of a human being is the environment in which he grows up and is the examples surrounding him.
On the tables of adipose children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had fries for dinner on the eve of the Enlightenment campaign under the motto "Adipositas is not a coincidence".
In families with Dickerchen sports are not exactly one of the favourite jobs, but as far as the majority of today's students are concerned - only 15 percent answered that their parents find themselves at least once a week for active exercise.
Survey among 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, in which almost 900 children from primary schools were interviewed throughout the Czech Republic.
This was already the second year of the action "Adipositas is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th classes have participated in the project.
Unhealthy food and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the alarmingly increasing number of overweight or even obesity children.
"For example, only half of the children surveyed indicated five times a day to eat breakfast-second breakfast-vesper dinner-one of the main conditions for a healthy diet," says one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative small things, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the students' families have breakfast.
And - in most families everyone has breakfast alone.
The worst was the finding, which is not breakfast at all in every tenth family.
Breakfast is considered to be the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey test showed, among other things, that many times unhealthy fries are consumed in the families of overweight children.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed are sportsmen, only less than half of their parents do so - only 15 percent.
Compose your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools), from offered opportunities according to appetite and opinion, to prepare their own food plan.
"What Czech children prefer between 12 and 15 in terms of diet is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and, of course, sweet foods.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet lemonade", is emphasized in the final report on this survey.
At lunch, that is, the main course, doughnuts won just before poultry.
Hull fruit almost didn't like the children at all and also the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very small.
Returning to Health
At the same time, however, the survey also showed that the children are quite willing to change their eating habits when they get the right information.
"The survey participants' control group, which completed the questionnaire after completing the enlightening lecture "Adipositas is not a coincidence", was in many cases a clear shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition", is mentioned in the results of the project.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began giving priority to ordinary water.
The children also crossed the questionnaire much more often poultry or fish as the main course of the day and were willing to eat less dumplings or sweet foods.
