V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The originally carefree journey is made through a series of completely avoidable, dilettant errors to the routine journey to the early shift.
Although it was possible to fulfill the ambitions to a large extent, what good is it if obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before he came to the barn tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
After all, he promised to move the already old series of games "Need for Speed" back into a new dimension and in the playable demonstrations he did not seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about how the passages that have been introduced fail, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But how you're used to it at NFS is in the end a lot different from what you expected.
Sure - potentially it is quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is narrowed by some unnecessary errors that are present in this series for more or less a few years.
So it's actually not a mistake anymore, but rather a sign of the incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure begins very well.
For the first time, it is introduced into history, whose main character Jack has certain personal problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, that is, on the west coast, you get on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and into more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different route and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don't have the impression that game would always offer the same thing.
Some environments are still very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the ride through the desert, through the autumn landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape seemed visually very pleasant.
Occasionally, untypical elements bring a little variation into the individual races.
In the desert, for example, you are surprised by a desert storm that greatly limits your vision.
In the mountains again one must be kept in hell that one is not spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well in a row.
It's only a few, but it's enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to pick up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you expect another personal duel with a single opponent.
And the police, who want to mess up the whole thing, get involved.
A novelty is passages where Jack leaves the car.
This is more about certain interactive animations in which Jack flees from someone and where the player needs to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
However, it is surprising that there are far fewer passages like that in the game than one would expect (concretely only three).
In the end, this is more of an advantage, because at least this element has no chance of getting bored - it belongs in the context of the above-mentioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model steps into the footsteps of the previous parts.
In other words, from today’s point of view, it does not rip out trees, but one could not claim that it would be bad.
If you're looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But an action-loaded race will continue to be quite just the right driving model, even though one could find better in competition.
Until then, everything is in good order.
Real problems only show up after a certain time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not entirely O.K.
A game of this kind can hardly be expected to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no impact on any object, how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: When you overtake or pass oncoming cars, you "strip" the other car easily in some places, but in other, almost identical situations you get into the sledding and twist wild pirouettes.
Or take the car straight to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter any more, but it's annoying all the time.
The restarts are solved this way: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then you throw the game back to the last stop of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
Once you've exhausted it, everything starts from the beginning.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something doesn't work, but you should rather not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, it doesn't even help to restart, because nothing helps but to learn the critical section from the head.
Very unpleasant is that the same things often happen at the same places.
For example, some curves have to be driven in a very specific way, otherwise you just don't fit through.
Otherwise, you will always meet "civil" cars in the same configuration at the appropriate location, no matter if you arrive as first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations when you see that the opponent comes by in front of a playful car, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to bypass them or brake them.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed so that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The competitors have further advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken in the same place by the same opponent and again here without regard to the time.
At the craziest, this is at the end of the game on the long bridge that you happen in the opposite direction.
The opponent obviously has to get one out of here on the devil.
And if he's already in front of you, he'll take a look at you, of course, so that at first you drive your own car a few times in lump.
Of course - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but this intention is so clear that it quickly misses you the joy of the game.
And that's a shame, because despite a simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining and sometimes even so action-loaded that you almost don't know where one of the heads is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "guilt" is about - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that can't cause boredom, or something quite different...
An unusual idea is also the change of cars during the race.
You should not overlook the gas stations on the track, because right here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the Serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game history goes also the task mode (challenges) - i.e. the races in the individual locations that you know from history.
There are not only medals here, but also experience points for your own profile, which is common to the tasks (challenges) and history.
In order to reach the higher level of the driver, different objects have to be unlocked: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is at the same time connected to the Autolog online function, which inter alia compares its own scores with those of other players and also provides other collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvers is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you come by car into a subway tunnel (meinwegen), where you rest on the tracks in the dark for a long time (meinwegen).
The tacho looks at numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (meinwegen), but there suddenly comes from behind a subway and uncompromisingly drives to scrap.
In our editorial work we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is not overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is in most cases quite appealing and sometimes even brilliant.
It is all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the frequency of image repetition slows down and this sometimes quite dramatic.
This concerns, however, in particular, the accidents with a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS does not benefit anyhow.
The sound playback is as far as O.K. and the soundtrack is tasteful.
In an effort to address as wide a scale as possible rather to young audiences, a soundtrack a lä was created "by everyone something" - but who buys such a game because of the music?!
The general impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game were not narrowed by the above-mentioned completely unnecessary mistakes, we could have argued with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game seems.
In itself a great pleasure, but one should be prepared for one to face these errors with the power of airport lights.
Concert of the "students of the Velvet Revolution" with singing ensembles of Karlsuniversity
The Festival Festa Academica now offers for the third time the refreshment of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution and this as well as music experience.
During the festival, the twenty professional and university choirs will be presented.
The festival focuses on the two concerts that take place on 17 November.
"Karlsuniversity has a large share in the festival."
"Among the participants is also the choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanities Studies, and the Festival Committee also includes the Rector Václav Hampl," said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organization team.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of specialist school choirs, which will take place on 17 November from 2 p.m. on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes the composition of the important Czech jazz player Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evening hours, the concert "Students of the Velvet Revolution" (Studenty samtu) takes place in the gala rooms of the Volkshaus in Vinohrady, where choirs of Karlsuniversity are also performed.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate the World Student Day and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but to present choral music at the highest level to the public and to promote creative cooperation among young people.
The main organizer is the association of Czech choirs in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler-Gymnasium.
Bohuslav Svoboda, the mayor of the capital Prague and Václav Hampl, took over the patronage of the entire event.
The festival takes place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and in Pardubice.
Apart from concerts, the schedule also includes numerous music meetings, student happenings, matinees and other events.
Detailed information is available on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
