IBM history: From cheese cutter to universal flights
Founded one hundred years ago in New York, the company IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
She took over the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the later company IBM laid the fusion of four companies whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They had technologies such as the famous flashcards to register the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint was the architect of this new company, who was also the chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired Thomas J. Watson, the head of the competition company, to help him manage the company.
This leader then even put the founders of IBM in the shade - based on Watson's ideas to this day the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson managed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production and distribution of all possible machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to cashier.
In the first four decades of running the company, Watson doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chief chair for forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped manage NASA flights to Space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the series IBM System/360.
A classic PC, which specified the computer standard of that time, came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thereby entered into the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the concept of "Smarter Planet".
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in previously unplanned areas, for example to improve the situation in transport and urban administration.
In the commercial sector, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform to help traders lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
Already in 1932, IBM established a branch in Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern European Centre is based in Prague, and there is also a world-level top research team that deals with voice recognition technology.
