Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
At the time, the travel agencies sold mainly only travel to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, and in the West they were only allowed to choose.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia embarked on a pro-Western course and therefore the journeys to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern bloc (also Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies offered travel in the West, but then they had to take huge snakes or also spend the night in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
This was not the case for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange pledge - the condition for an exit to the West - was given only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought themselves countless weekend houses and datschen - a habit that continues to this day.
The combined revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on foot.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, one of which is no longer aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989 at all, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
From the beginning of the 1990s onwards, the obligation to pay foreign exchange was lifted in the neighbouring countries of Western Europe, resulting in a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymakers slept when traveling to Paris in the tent in the park, because who had already had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension.
A typical feature of travel abroad from the Czech Republic was at that time a packed trunk full of canned, beer and permanent sausage.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists could finally buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of living and thus our average salaries also increased, which in 1997 meant another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to prepare charter flights regularly after 1997, which made flights incredibly affordable compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already had currency-free payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post office" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was completed - to Thailand.
Since then, charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying directly from the Czech Republic every year to distant sunny countries; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flown directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Tsd Czechs travel every year to exotic countries!
Another important moment in the era that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17th, 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which made our country definitely among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008 the Czechs spent for the first time more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 TZK per head for a single holiday including the costs at the resort.
