To recognize lies or to "discover" lies is one that is important for every human being, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as Sharaden, in which the goal is to call "Hab you!", detaching a deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at respected universities that carried out far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most old myths have been deflected from the lie.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, stammer, rot and gag.
However, it must not be concluded that these liars are difficult to uncover and detach.
A trained liar deterrent can penetrate the truth by learning something about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years investigating the scientific results of the comprehensive and ever-growing field of deforestation, and it is clear that defacing a deception is a modern ability that is easy to learn and helps us to find justice in our complex world, especially if the setting up or questioning of persons or negotiations or administration is one of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appraising other people, raising their interest and controlling their own emotions, and they feel intuitively how they are perceived by others.
