First, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called "baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluation of changes.
Watch the attitude, laughter, voice quality of your subject.
You should know better when someone normally keeps tripping with his foot, so that they do not unjustly accuse him when he triples with his foot during a meeting.
Then watch out for accumulations of noticeable verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
