Climatic hardships slowed the economy
In the first year that Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloas. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who calls himself the initiator of change and holds great hopes of economic growth, is in the government. However, due to climatic imbalances, growth cannot be the talk of growth, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses in the agricultural sector at millions, but also limited the growth of the national economy and caused a general fall in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development of 31.16 percent, which slowed down the impact on other sectors of the economy.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of the frost, 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, 78.03 per cent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 per cent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity by November has steadily increased unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, for from January to March 55 053 residents of Sinaloas had no employment, corresponding to 4.53 per cent of the labour force. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 per cent and from July to September to 6.19 per cent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18,969 more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa this year is due to several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that public institutions' policies indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment, which has several factors to do with, among other things, the loss of liquidity in the market as a result of the cutbacks by the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are prohibited from raising dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen, due to the problems of entry and, on the one hand, because it is difficult to find work there. These people stay here and are looking for work to increase unemployment," he says.
Undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if the high proportion of undeclared work is taken into account.
Unemployment and undeclared work are the lowest wages in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of employees in Sinaloa was up to September 5352 pesos, which is much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Reduction of the ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, the biggest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years was recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI from January to June amounted to 630 597 dollars, representing a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the 5,143 312 dollars in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Authority for Economic Development) has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In the face of the economic crisis, in July, the state government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, Mario López Valdé's first year of government made it clear that he was incapacitated.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing in Mexico), said that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the various sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really poor this year. It has to be worked hard to regain the lost terrain this year and in 2012 we have to make double efforts. The efforts of all and especially the progress of the already well-coordinated government team have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important impacts is a slow-down economy that is not moving enough to generate an economic dynamic that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will complete the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexico Business Association) in Sinaloa, said that the state should be given more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources Sinaloas," he said.
There's a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will lead to better government efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which it can be said that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
