The possibility of counting the ballots in Michoacán individually is considered
According to the information provided by PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the governor's election is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of individual counting of the ballot is a reality this year in the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data provided by the Programmea de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP) the difference between the first and second place in the governorial elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
To this end, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November, the electoral office adopted a number of arrangements to harmonise local rules with the reforms of the federal states in electoral matters.
It should be remembered that Michoacán had neither adapted his political constitution nor his electoral law nor his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they had not entered into force during this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the public prosecutor within the time limits provided for by the argument or objection.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional appeal filed by the local legislature and assessed the vote of the State Commissioner on constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal", since he did not have the right to "determine or veto it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal stated in an interview on the possibility of individual counting of votes that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by Consejo General del IEM, there would now be the possibility that the local electoral authority could partially or completely count the ballot.
Thus, in the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted.The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not available in due course or they are not in the hands of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or changes in the minutes.
In addition, if there is a difference between the presumed winner and the one in second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, the total number of full-filled ballots may be counted, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the candidates mentioned.
The vote can also be counted in its entirety if, after completion of the proper calculation, it is established that the difference between the presumed winner and the candidate is second or lower than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the election packages that have been partially counted would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between the first and second place is almost 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of 923 votes have not yet been counted.
