The social security institution of Mexico is conducting a research project to find the genes for obesity in children and adolescents, supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexico's Social Insurance Institute) announced that it will lead a research project on the discovery of obesity genes in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth" with which the genetic markers are to be found in association with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Department of Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team, consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers, was established.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested people can come to the sports grounds of the IMSS in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and young people are carried out every Saturday from 8.00 am.
He stressed that the investigation began at the Cuahtémoc sports field (to the west of the state of México) and was continued since 8 October at the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (to the east of the state of México).
Once the target of 500 to 600 investigators has been reached, the study will be continued at the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and will be completed at the site of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He stated that the aim of the study was to identify the factors and role of genetics in the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors for Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the worldwide day of diabetes, he stated that three thousand children and young people aged six to 14 years should be filled in with the consent and supervision of their parents with food-related questionnaires.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and their family history to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He further explained that on Saturdays the investigators measured (weight, size, waist size), their blood pressure and blood levels such as glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (test for the identification of genes related to obesity in childhood) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this study would be carried out in response to health care professionals' concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"Health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of obese girls increased by 47 percent. Overweight also increased dramatically," said the specialist of the IMSS.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico was different from that of other peoples.
He stated that one (e) Mexican (in) is on average 65 percent Indian-American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, reflecting the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity were incapacitating itself in the inability to burn the excess of energy (calories) taken to us, so that it would be stored in the form of fat.
