Asphalt of the UNAM prevents pitfalls
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM University of Mexico, develops modified asphalts with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
It would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 000 pitfalls if the rainy season broke out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning and ensuring that if the layout and maintenance of the asphalt coating were appropriately damaged, the number of pitfalls would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Slagholes from a technical point of view", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible developed modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Mrera Nájera argued that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of pitfalls.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, some of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low one - the so-called Malthene. Together they give to the road surface its characteristic toelastic behaviour.
The countastic behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and at 50°C it is almost firm, while at very low temperatures it becomes fragile.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," said the chemical engineer.
The researcher at the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of them a flexible road surface consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the upper strata lies a layer of asphalt that consists of small, asphalted and then fortified stones.
Every single stone of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "a last layer is laid out, the so-called bearing layer consisting of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
In addition, most of the power received and distributed by this road surface requires a suitable thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water penetrates the layer and escapes only difficult again. This causes the dislocation of all layers of the road surface and consequently the appearance of strokes.
When a punch hole arises," he said, "the top layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected after that. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexico's National Research System) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of pitfalls. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent pitfalls.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there were still a lot of research work to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions that were already on the market in other countries, with which the pitfalls could be easily repaired without the use of high temperatures.
