Entry of a "Golden Budget Rule" into the Constitution
On Tuesday, the Austrian government of the great Social-Democratic/Christian-Democratic coalition decided to include a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution to reduce public deficits and also to avoid possible degradation by rating agencies in Austria's top-level government (AAA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann personally who had announced this decision from the outcome of the Council of Ministers, although the public debt of Austria is 74.6%, far above the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the level of debt of the countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's ability to pay was not reduced to a blow from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion Euros of interest each year," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice-Chancellor and Christian-Democratic Foreign Minister.
Austria also requests the Brussels Eurozone Member States Summit of 26 October: the Heads of State or Government would then have demanded the inclusion of the reduction of public deficits by the end of 2012 and the return to the public balance of accounts in the Constitution or the adoption of an equivalent law.
The measure taken by the Austrian government is similar to the "German model", since Germany had been the first European country to have incorporated such a "rule" into the constitution.
By 2017, the structural budget deficit should decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year; by 2017, the structural budget deficit of the state should not exceed the 0.35% of GDP, whereas regional governments and municipalities should have balanced budgets.
The aim is to eliminate the budgetary debt under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Agreement in the 2020/21 horizon.
