North Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with brilliance and Gloria.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, lived on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sound and at fine-tasting buffet the inauguration of the new North Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have symbolically turned the control of the valve, which transports the Russian gas into the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe through a first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the St Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total delivery of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of total French consumption - is expected to be completed by the end of 2012.
And one already lets the possibility of building a third line sound on its own.
For Gazprom, the timely and accurate completion of this huge building seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The North Stream pipeline will enable direct gas delivery to Germany, while avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on the land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little of their power: it is now becoming more difficult for them to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most strongly engaged in the debate, was not shyed away from comparing the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Swiss pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of reducing European energy, as the project has struck a break between Western and Eastern Europe.
Russia has completed its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas deposits are on the decline in just under five years.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," confirmed François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the major gas contracts are also important from a political and economic point of view.
All of this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The submersible pipe consists of steel with concrete covering, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, about 200 m deep.
Mining fields dating from the Second World War had to be removed during their construction.
"Some hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed carefully," said Jens Müller, spokesperson of Nord Stream.
In addition, reinforced measures were needed to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long hose made of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is interrupted by nothing over the entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project managers have refused to do so, as Sweden has little interest in seeing a Russian state company settle on the shores of its shores in a permanent manner.
"In the event of a disaster, we close the gas throughput in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the case of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the constructors to be less likely, since the welding seams were estimated to be resistant by one leak per 100,000 years.
State control of gas transmission is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes by a seaship, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas transmission line.
It has the shape of a cigar, has a diameter of one metre, is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is moved through the gas pressure.
After three complete days of movement through the wire at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on its arrival about any deformation of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without even having to undergo the smallest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have united their forces to carry out this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E. ON and BASF (each 15.5%), as well as the Dutch gas union and the French group GDF Suez (each to 9%), are associated here.
These five companies have formed a community of companies called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It has its seat in train in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, on a renewable 20-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real transporter gas volume falls," Jens Müller explained.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% of shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment total was 240 million.
The minority shareholders, however, are aware of recovering their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline emerges on a sandy coastline forested with pine trees near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other parameters of the incoming gas before it is passed on to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with a million cubic metres of Russian gas per hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a trademark notebook.
Founded by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give the writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, with candlelights spent with writing hours.
The notebook of Moleskine is easily recognizable, with its black, rectangular cover, its rubber band, the eggshell-coloured sides, as over time aged.
However, the Moleskin notebook, as it is known today, was created in 1997.
At the time, the Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided to publish a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, at that time specialist consultant of the company, is responsible for the market launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an ancient production technique called Mole Skin (mole skin), which is called a cotton varnish used for covering upholstery benches.
This type of notebook was very much in demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object, which until the 20th century was regarded as an icon of avant-garde artists," explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success is on the rise.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales rose by 26% and established themselves with a sales volume of 12.7 million pieces.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine passes the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook inspires businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded customers.
The small, Italian company, which initially employed 12 people, employs over 100 people today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookstores, on Internet portals such as Fnac, in small city centre boutiques and understands how to enforce its identity.
"We have followed the zeitgeist and his new need for writing, which exists despite the recovery of the e-mails," said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: Recently, the brand launched an exposure called "Detour" in which architects and artists issued their own notebooks.
In August, at the film festival in Locarno, the company also launched a cover with leopard patterns.
Moleskine benefited from his success and this cultural zeitgeist and understood to diversify his products: bags, appointment calendar, fillers, computer cases... The brand has the entire range of articles.
A success that brings envy to the plan: In autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought up by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today's Syntegra Capital, and thus proposed a new chapter in Moleskine's history.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th week of work for the disabled".
Despite a determined public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice the average average: 19% compared to 9% of the total population.
Discouraging?
"No, this is how Éric Blanchet, Director-General of the Adapt Association, emphasises the "week of work for the disabled."
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
"At that time the unemployment rate was not twice as high, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, there is still a great deal to be done."
However, it must be said that there are still many obstacles for the disabled unemployed before they get a job.
It is more common for the elderly: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low qualification level: 80% of them do not have a degree and there are only 10,000 disabled among the 2.3 million students with higher education qualifications.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% for the disabled compared with 38% for the total.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it more difficult to start working again and that form the "core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992, which helps companies to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the actual brakes.
Keep the unspoken, the mental attitudes that, although certain, but slowly evolve.
A study carried out in April by the Association of IMS Entreprendre for the magazine La Cité indicated that the managers surveyed have "a weak level of knowledge about the disabled" which was "overrepresented" by people in wheelchairs, mental or intellectually inferior.
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go in order to achieve the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, which was laid down in a 1987 law.
These latter figures from 2008 refer to a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now at 3%," reports Pierre Blanc, Director-General of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that disregard this law.
Evidence: The number of "fees paid" establishments has decreased from 59.000 to 46.000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros) as well as the sum of the sums paid between 2007 and 2011.
"The 2005 Law, which provides for increased contributions, created a strong pressure on the companies," explained Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also reflects a real understanding, especially of the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of establishments employ disabled workers between 20 and 49 employees, while enterprises with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
